g yeast cells in tissue","Produces septate hyphae with 45-degree branching","Forms encapsulated yeast cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct characteristic feature of \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E species is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduces septate hyphae with 45-degree branching\u003C/strong\u003E.  This morphology can be observed in tissue specimens using special stains like Gomori methenamine silver or periodic acid-Schiff. This distinctive microscopic appearance, along with the presence of conidiophores bearing chains of conidia, is key to identifying \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent features of other fungi:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms budding yeast cells in tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrows as spherules containing endospores\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces broad nonseptate hyphae\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of Mucormycetes like \u003Cem\u003ERhizopus\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms encapsulated yeast cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspergillus fumigatus is the most common species causing invasive aspergillosis in immunocompromised patients.","Aspergillus species are ubiquitous environmental fungi that reproduce via airborne conidia.","Aspergillus species can cause allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, aspergilloma, and invasive aspergillosis."]